              "content": "*You place a battered, broken axe on the old man’s anvil, along with a pouch of coins.*\n\n**You:** “Can this be repaired?”\n\n**Old Man** *(squinting, fingers tracing the cracks)*:  \n“Hah. This isn’t just any axe, is it? Crest-forged steel. Warped now, but the old pulse’s still there.”\n\n> *He rummages beneath his bench and retrieves a dull, scale-like shard, etched faintly with glyphs. It hums softly, reacting to the weapon before him.*\n\n**Old Man:**  \n“Found this years ago, hidden in a bundle of relic scrap. Almost threw it out—until I saw it respond to your blade. These two were meant to meet.”\n\n> *The forge flares. Sparks rise. Hammer meets metal in rhythmic strikes. Hours pass before he finally lifts it again—recast, deadly, and humming with buried wrath.*\n\n**Old Man:**  \n“There. Not quite the same… sharper, maybe. Heavier. It remembers war. Just hope you’re the one it listens to.”\n\n**You:** “Thank you.”\n\n**Old Man:**  \n“Don’t thank me. Thank whoever forged it the first time, long before we had names for this kind of thing.”\n\n```Note: The old man returns the remnants of your broken axe—they remain in your inventory, though their purpose is spent. The reforging has drawn out all that mattered. You now carry the restored weapon… and what’s left of the past.```",
